1. Business Understanding¶

1.1 Business Problem¶

Process optimization for stud welding technology

1.2 Client(s)¶

Brian Madalinski, stud weld process engineer

1.3 Objective¶

The goal is to understand what features contribute most to Weld Out of Process and create a model that can predict if a certain weld will cause an out of process condition.

1.4 Description¶

Emhart stud welding is a vital process to the Body Shop in ensuring the joining integrity of the car body as it is being pieced and welded together prior to going into the paint process. Currently there are multiple welding processes to make this happen. Stud welding is one of these processes.

def plot_histograms( df , variables , n_rows , n_cols ):
    fig = plt.figure( figsize = ( 16 , 12 ) )
    for i, var_name in enumerate( variables ):
        ax=fig.add_subplot( n_rows , n_cols , i+1 )
        df[ var_name ].hist( bins=10 , ax=ax )
        ax.set_title( 'Skew: ' + str( round( float( df[ var_name ].skew() ) , ) ) ) # + ' ' + var_name ) #var_name+" Distribution")
        ax.set_xticklabels( [] , visible=False )
        ax.set_yticklabels( [] , visible=False )
    fig.tight_layout()  # Improves appearance a bit.
    plt.show()

def plot_distribution( df , var , target , **kwargs ):
    row = kwargs.get( 'row' , None )
    col = kwargs.get( 'col' , None )
    facet = sns.FacetGrid( df , hue=target , aspect=4 , row = row , col = col )
    facet.map( sns.kdeplot , var , shade= True )
    facet.set( xlim=( 0 , df[ var ].max() ) )
    facet.add_legend()

def plot_categories( df , cat , target , **kwargs ):
    row = kwargs.get( 'row' , None )
    col = kwargs.get( 'col' , None )
    facet = sns.FacetGrid( df , row = row , col = col )
    facet.map( sns.barplot , cat , target )
    facet.add_legend()

def plot_correlation_map( df ):
    corr = df.corr()
    _ , ax = plt.subplots( figsize =( 12 , 10 ) )
    cmap = sns.diverging_palette( 220 , 10 , as_cmap = True )
    _ = sns.heatmap(
        corr, 
        cmap = cmap,
        square=True, 
        cbar_kws={ 'shrink' : .9 }, 
        ax=ax, 
        annot = True, 
        annot_kws = { 'fontsize' : 12 }
    )

def describe_more( df ):
    var = [] ; l = [] ; t = []
    for x in df:
        var.append( x )
        l.append( len( pd.value_counts( df[ x ] ) ) )
        t.append( df[ x ].dtypes )
    levels = pd.DataFrame( { 'Variable' : var , 'Levels' : l , 'Datatype' : t } )
    levels.sort_values( by = 'Levels' , inplace = True )
    return levels

2.3 Feature Understanding with units of measure for process data¶

  • Device Name: Robot ID
  • Type: WIP or WOP, Weld In Parameter or Weld out of Parameter (OK vs NOK)
  • Fault Number: If there was a fault the corresponding fault classification
  • Stud-ID: Stud Number
  • Carbody ID: Carbody ID (Does this come from PLUS?)
  • Remark:
  • Date/Time: Date and Time
  • Application: Steel or Cleanflash Aluminum
  • Outlet/Feeder/Tool: Self-Explanatory
  • Tool type: Categorical Feature of Different Stud Weld tools
  • MAC Process: Not Active for all records
  • MAC Reference/-current: Not Used
  • System Weld Counter: For a gun at given time, how many welds since last time the gun was reset
  • Tool Weld Counter: A gun at given time since resest
  • Outlet Weld Counter WOP: NOK controler is capable of 3 guns, WOP counter
  • Outlet Weld Counter: Same thing but total
  • Optimization: Do not use
  • Clean Time: Aluminum welding precleaning time
  • Peak/Drop Voltage: Not used (V)
  • Mode: Force / Position Mode Try to achieve Force mode
  • Stickout (Ref/Actual): How far stud sticks past the reference sustainer, must have more stickout (mm)
  • Droptime (Ref/Actual): How long it takes from top position for linear motor to bottom position (ms)
  • Weldmode: Steel = Normal, Aluminum
  • Message: Not used
  • Pilot Weldcurrent Arc Voltage Reference (Up): Strikes the arc and cleans the stud (V)
  • Pilot Weldcurrent Arc Voltage Minimum (Up): Strikes the arc and cleans the stud (V)
  • Pilot Weldcurrent Arc Voltage Maximum (Up): Strikes the arc and cleans the stud (V)
  • Pilot Weldcurrent Arc Voltage Actual (Up): Strikes the arc and cleans the stud (V)
  • Main Weldcurent Voltage Reference (Us): Main welding measure (V)
  • Main Welcurrent Voltage Minimum (Us): Main welding measure (V)
  • Main Weldcurrent Voltage Maximum (Us): Main welding measure (V)
  • Main Weldcurrent Voltage Actual (Us): Main welding measure (V)
  • Weldcurrent Reference (Is): Main welding measure (A)
  • Weldcurrent Minimum (Is): Main welding measure (A)
  • Weldcurrent Maximum (Is): Main welding measure (A)
  • Weldcurrent Actual (Is): Main welding measure (A)
  • Weldtime Reference (It): Main welding measure (ms)
  • Weldtime Minimum (It): Main welding measure (ms)
  • Weldtime Maximum (It): Main welding measure (ms)
  • Weldtime Actual (It): Main Welding Measure (ms)
  • Weld Energy Reference (Es): Main welding measure (J)
  • Weld Energy Minimum (Es): Main welding measure (J)
  • Weld Energy Maximum (Es): Main welding measure (J)
  • Weld Energy Actual (Es): Main welding measure (J)
  • Lift Height Reference: Programmed the linear motor pulls the stud up (mm)
  • Lift Height Minimum: Programmed the linear motor pulls the stud up (mm)
  • Lift Height Maximum: Programmed the linear motor pulls the stud up (mm)
  • Lift Height Actual: Programmed the linear motor pulls the stud up (mm)
  • Penetration Reference (P): How far down the linear motor pushes the metal (mm)
  • Penetration Minimum (P): How far down the linear motor pushes the metal (mm)
  • Penetration Maximum (P): How far down the linear motor pushes the metal (mm)
  • Penetration Actual (P): How far down the linear motor pushes the metal (mm)

Statistical Test for Correlation¶

One-Sample T-Test (Measuring Weldtime Actual)¶

A one sample t-test checks whether a sample mean differs from the population mean. Let's test to see whether the mean Weldtime Actual for FS73 160RB400 differs from the entire population.

Hypothesis Testing: Is there significant difference in the means of Weldtime Actual between FS73 160RB400 and the entire population?

  • Null Hypothesis: (H0 = pPS = pPP) The null hypothesis would be that there is no difference in Weldtime Actual between FS73 160RB400 and the entire population.
  • Alternative Hypothesis: (HA:pPS != pPP) The alternative hypothesis would be that there is a difference in mean Weldtime Actual between FS73 160RB400 and the entire population.
In [35]:
# Let's compare the means of Weldtime Actual data against the Weldtime Actual population data
weldtime1 = df['Weldtime  Actual (It)'].mean()
weldtime2 = df[df['Device Name']=='FS73 160RB400']['Weldtime  Actual (It)'].mean()

print('The mean Weldtime Actual of the population is: ' + str(weldtime1))
print('The mean Weldtime Actual of FS73 160RB400 is: ' + str(weldtime2))

The mean Weldtime Actual of the population is: 550.1856359965388
The mean Weldtime Actual of FS73 160RB400 is: 555.3825861543154

Conducting the T-Test¶

Let's conduct a t-test at 95% confidence level and see if it correctly rejects the null hypothesis that the same comes from the same distribution as the population. To conduct a one-sample t-test, we can use the stats.ttest_1samp() function:

In [36]:
import scipy.stats as stats
stats.ttest_1samp(a=  df[df['Device Name']=='FS73 160RB400']['Weldtime  Actual (It)'],
                  popmean = weldtime1, nan_policy ='omit')
Out[36]:
Ttest_1sampResult(statistic=3.7015781278115187, pvalue=0.00021601991263819702)

T-Test Result¶

The test result shows the test statistic "t" is equal to 3.702. This test statistic tells us how much the sample mean deviates from the null hypothesis. If the t-statistic lies outside the quantiles of the t-distribution corresponding to our confidence level and degrees of freedom, we reject the null hypothese. We can check the quantiles with stats.t.ppf()

T-Test Quantile¶

If the test statistic value we calculated above (3.702) is outside the quartiles, then we can reject the null hypothesis.

In [37]:
degree_freedom = len(df[df['Device Name']=='FS73 160RB400'])

LQ = stats.t.ppf(0.025, degree_freedom) # Left Quartile

RQ = stats.t.ppf(0.975, degree_freedom) # Right Quartile

print("The t-distirbution left quartile range is: " + str(LQ))
print("The t-distribution right quartile range is: " + str(RQ))

The t-distirbution left quartile range is: -1.9603257871749862
The t-distribution right quartile range is: 1.9603257871749857

One-Sample T-Test Summary¶

T-Test = 3.702 | P-Value = .000216 | Reject Null Hypothesis

Reject the null hypothesis because:

  • T-Test score is outside the quartiles
  • P-value is lower than confidence level of 5%

Based on the statistical analysis of a one sample t-test, there seems to be some significant difference between the mean Weldtime Actual for FS73 160RB400 and the entire population mean Weldtime Actual. The low P-value of .000216 at a 5% confidence level is a good indicator to reject the null hypothesis.

But this does not neccessarily mean that there is practical significance. We would have to conduct more experiments or maybe collect more data about the in order to come up with a more accurate finding.

4.0 Modeling the Data¶

The best model performance out of the four (Decision Tree Model, AdaBoost Model, Logisitc Regression Model, Random Forest Model) was Decision Tree

Note on Base Rate

  • A Base Rate Model is a model that always selects the target variable's majority class. It's just used for reference to compare how better another model is against it. In this dataset, the majority class that will be predicted will be WIPs, which are welds that were in process.
  • If you recall back to Exploring the Data, 97.5% of the FS73 160RB400 dataset contained WIPs (Welds in Process) and the remaining 2.5% contained WOPs (Welds out of process). The Base Rate Model would simply predict every stud weld as WIP and ignore all the WOPs.
  • Example: The base rate accuracy for this data set, when classifying everything as WIPs, would be 97.5%, because 97.5% of the dataset are labeled as WIPs (Welds in process).

Note: Evaluating the Model

Precision and Recall / Class Imbalance

This dataset is an example of a class imbalance problem because of the skewed distribution of WIP vs WOP. More skewed the class means that accuracy breaks down.

In this case, evaluating our models algorithm based on accuracy is the wrong thing to measure. We would have to know the different errors that we care about and correct decisions. Accuracy alone does not measure an important concept that needs to be taken into consideration in this type of evaluation: False Positive and False Negative errors.

False Positives (Type I Error): You predict that the weld will be in a WIP condition, but it is not.

False Negatives (Type II Error): You predict that the weld will not be in a WIP condition, but it is.

In this problem, what type of errors do we care about more? False Positives or False Negatives?

Note: Different Ways to Evaluate Classification Models

  1. Predictive Accuracy: How many does it get right?
  2. Speed: How fast does it take for the model to deploy?
  3. Scalability: Can the model handle large datasets?
  4. Robustness: How well does the model handle outliers/missing values?
  5. Interpretability: Is the model easy to understand?
